Ashish Vaswani
Ashish Vaswani is affiliated with Google Brain and contributed equally to the work, involved in designing and implementing the first Transformer models.

Noam Shazeer
Noam Shazeer is affiliated with Google Brain and contributed equally to the work, proposed scaled dot-product attention, multi-head attention, and the parameter-free position representation.<SEP>Noam Shazeer is an author of a paper on outrageously large neural networks.<SEP>Noam Shazeer is an author of papers on exploring the limits of language modeling and outrageously large neural networks.

Niki Parmar
Niki Parmar is affiliated with Google Research and contributed equally to the work, designed, implemented, tuned, and evaluated countless model variants.

Jakob Uszkoreit
Jakob Uszkoreit is affiliated with Google Research and contributed equally to the work, proposed replacing RNNs with self-attention and started the effort to evaluate this idea.<SEP>Jakob Uszkoreit is an author of a paper on a decomposable attention model.

Llion Jones
Llion Jones is affiliated with Google Research and contributed equally to the work, experimented with novel model variants, was responsible for the initial codebase, and efficient inference and visualizations.

Aidan N. Gomez
Aidan N. Gomez is affiliated with the University of Toronto and contributed equally to the work, spent countless long days designing various parts of and implementing tensor2tensor.

Łukasz Kaiser
Łukasz Kaiser is affiliated with Google Brain and contributed equally to the work, spent countless long days designing various parts of and implementing tensor2tensor, replacing the earlier codebase.<SEP>Łukasz Kaiser is an author of papers on neural GPUs learn algorithms and can active memory replace attention.

Illia Polosukhin
Illia Polosukhin is affiliated and contributed equally to the work, designed and implemented the first Transformer models.

Google Brain
Google Brain is a research organization where some of the authors are affiliated, involved in the development of the Transformer model.

Google Research
Google Research is a research organization where some of the authors are affiliated, involved in the development of the Transformer model.

University of Toronto
University of Toronto is an academic institution where Aidan N. Gomez is affiliated.

WMT 2014 English-to-German Translation Task
WMT 2014 English-to-German translation task is a machine translation benchmark where the Transformer model achieved 28.4 BLEU.

WMT 2014 English-to-French Translation Task
WMT 2014 English-to-French translation task is a machine translation benchmark where the Transformer model achieved a new single-model state-of-the-art BLEU score of 41.0.

Long Beach, CA, USA
Long Beach, CA, USA is the location of the 31st Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NIPS 2017).

31st Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NIPS 2017)
31st Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NIPS 2017) is a conference where the paper was presented.

Machine Translation
A category of natural language processing tasks that involve translating text from one language to another.<SEP>Machine Translation is a category of tasks that the Transformer model addresses.<SEP>Machine translation is the automated translation of text from one language to another.

Transformer
A novel network architecture based solely on attention mechanisms, dispensing with recurrence and convolutions.<SEP>A transduction model that relies entirely on self-attention to compute representations of its input and output without using sequence-aligned RNNs or convolution.<SEP>The Transformer is a model that uses multi-head attention in three different ways: encoder-decoder attention, self-attention in the encoder, and self-attention in the decoder.<SEP>The Transformer is a sequence transduction model based entirely on attention mechanisms, replacing recurrent layers in encoder-decoder architectures.<SEP>Transformer is a new simple network architecture based solely on attention mechanisms.

Attention Is All You Need
Title of the research paper introducing the Transformer model.

Sequence Transduction Models
The dominant models for sequence transduction, which the Transformer aims to improve upon.

Recurrent Neural Networks
A type of neural network architecture used for sequence modeling.<SEP>A type of neural network that the Transformer replaces, known for sequential computation.

Convolutional Neural Networks
Another type of neural network that the Transformer replaces, used in sequence modeling.

Encoder
A component of sequence transduction models that processes the input sequence.<SEP>A component of the Transformer model that maps an input sequence of symbol representations to a sequence of continuous representations.<SEP>The encoder is a component of the Transformer model that contains self-attention layers and feed-forward networks.<SEP>The encoder is a part of sequence transduction models, mapping an input sequence to a sequence of hidden representations.

Decoder
A component of sequence transduction models that generates the output sequence.<SEP>A component of the Transformer model that generates an output sequence of symbols one element at a time based on the encoder's output.<SEP>The decoder is a component of the Transformer model that contains self-attention layers, encoder-decoder attention layers, and feed-forward networks. It generates the output sequence.<SEP>The decoder is a part of sequence transduction models, mapping a sequence of hidden representations to an output sequence.

Attention Mechanism
A mechanism used to connect the encoder and decoder, and the core component of the Transformer.

Machine Translation Tasks
Tasks used to evaluate the performance of the Transformer model.

BLEU
A metric used to evaluate the quality of machine translation output.<SEP>A metric used to evaluate the quality of machine translation.<SEP>BLEU (Bilingual Evaluation Understudy) is a metric for evaluating the quality of machine translation output.

P100 GPUs
Hardware used to train the Transformer model.

Long Short-Term Memory
A type of recurrent neural network.

Gated Recurrent
A type of recurrent neural network.

Sequence Modeling
A field that uses recurrent neural networks.

Transduction Problems
A field that uses recurrent neural networks.

Language Modeling
A category of natural language processing tasks that involve predicting the probability of a sequence of words.<SEP>A type of sequence modeling.

Encoder-Decoder Architectures
A type of architecture used in sequence modeling.<SEP>A type of neural network architecture commonly used for sequence transduction tasks.

RNNs
Abbreviation for Recurrent Neural Networks.<SEP>Recurrent Neural Networks, a type of neural network architecture, specifically sequence-aligned RNNs, which the Transformer aims to replace with self-attention.

Self-Attention
An attention mechanism relating different positions of a single sequence to compute a representation of the sequence.<SEP>An attention mechanism relating different positions of a single sequence.<SEP>Self-Attention is a mechanism used for mapping variable-length sequences, connecting all positions with a constant number of sequentially executed operations.

Extended Neural GPU
An architecture that uses convolutional neural networks.

ByteNet
An architecture that uses convolutional neural networks.<SEP>ByteNet is a neural machine translation model.

ConvS2S
An architecture that uses convolutional neural networks.<SEP>ConvS2S is a convolutional sequence-to-sequence model used for machine translation.

Multi-Head Attention
A type of attention used in the Transformer.<SEP>An attention mechanism used to counteract the effects of attention-weighted positions.<SEP>Multi-head attention is a mechanism that allows the model to jointly attend to information from different representation subspaces at different positions.

Reading Comprehension
A task that uses self-attention.

Abstractive Summarization
A category of natural language processing tasks that involve generating summaries of text.<SEP>A task that uses self-attention.

Textual Entailment
A task that uses self-attention.

Tensor2tensor
A codebase used to implement the Transformer.

Scaled Dot-Product Attention
A specific type of attention mechanism used, involving the computation of dot products between queries and keys, scaled by the square root of the dimension of the keys.

Convolution
A mathematical operation used in signal processing and image analysis, and an alternative to self-attention that the Transformer avoids.

End-To-End Memory Networks
A type of neural network architecture based on a recurrent attention mechanism, used for question answering and language modeling.

Additive Attention
An attention function using a feed-forward network to compute compatibility, an alternative to dot-product attention.

Dot-Product Attention
An attention function that computes compatibility using dot products, similar to scaled dot-product attention but without the scaling factor.

Layer Normalization
A technique for normalizing the activations of a neural network layer.<SEP>A technique used to normalize the outputs of each layer to improve training stability and speed.

Feed-Forward Network
A type of neural network with fully connected layers used in both additive attention and within the encoder and decoder stacks of the Transformer.

Q
Matrix of queries used in the Scaled Dot-Product Attention mechanism.<SEP>Q represents the queries in the attention mechanism.

K
K represents the keys in the attention mechanism.<SEP>Matrix of keys used in the Scaled Dot-Product Attention mechanism.

V
Matrix of values used in the Scaled Dot-Product Attention mechanism.<SEP>V represents the values in the attention mechanism.

Figure 1
A diagram depicting the Transformer model architecture, including encoder and decoder stacks.

Figure 2
A diagram illustrating Scaled Dot-Product Attention and Multi-Head Attention mechanisms.

ReLU
ReLU is an activation function used in the feed-forward network of the encoder and decoder layers.

Softmax Function
The softmax function is used to convert the decoder output to predicted next-token probabilities.

Positional Encoding
Positional encodings are added to the input embeddings to provide information about the position of tokens in the sequence.

WMT 2014 English-German Dataset
The WMT 2014 English-German dataset is a standard dataset consisting of about 4.5 million sentence pairs used for training models.

WMT 2014 English-French Dataset
The WMT 2014 English-French dataset is a larger dataset consisting of 36M sentences used for training models.

NVIDIA P100 GPUs
NVIDIA P100 GPUs are hardware used for training the models, with the training done on one machine with 8 GPUs.

Positional Encodings
Positional encodings are added to embeddings to provide information about the position of tokens in a sequence.

Sine and Cosine Functions
Sine and cosine functions of different frequencies are used as positional encodings.

Word-Piece
Word-piece representations are used in machine translation models.

Byte-Pair
Byte-pair representations are used in machine translation models.

Convolutional Layers
Convolutional layers are used for mapping variable-length sequences and are compared to self-attention layers.<SEP>Layers in a neural network that process data using convolution operations.

Recurrent Layers
Layers in a neural network that process sequential data.<SEP>Recurrent layers are used for mapping variable-length sequences and are compared to self-attention layers.

WMT 2014
WMT 2014 is a machine translation competition and dataset provider.<SEP>WMT 2014 is a machine translation competition used to evaluate the performance of translation models.

English-German Dataset
The English-German dataset is used for training machine translation models.

English-French Dataset
The English-French dataset is used for training machine translation models.

NVIDIA
NVIDIA is a technology company known for designing and manufacturing graphics processing units (GPUs).<SEP>NVIDIA is a technology company that produces GPUs used for training machine learning models.

Geometric Progression
Geometric progression is the pattern with which wavelengths form the positional encoding.

P100
P100 GPUs are high-performance GPUs used for training machine learning models.<SEP>P100 is a type of GPU with a specified TFLOPS value of 9.5.

Adam
Adam is an optimization algorithm used in training machine learning models.

Deep-Att + PosUnk
Deep-Att + PosUnk is a neural machine translation model that incorporates deep attention mechanisms and positional embeddings.

GNMT + RL is Google's Neural Machine Translation system with Reinforcement Learning.

MoE
MoE refers to Mixture of Experts, a model architecture used for machine translation.

Transformer (base model)
The Transformer (base model) is a baseline model architecture for machine translation, as described in the paper.

Transformer (big)
The Transformer (big) is a larger version of the Transformer model, with increased capacity and performance.

English-to-German Translation

English-to-French Translation
English-to-French translation is a specific task in machine translation.

Source Tokens
Source tokens represent the input sequence in a machine translation task.

Target Tokens

Base Models
The base models are the standard Transformer models used for comparison.

Big Models
The big models are larger Transformer models with more parameters, used for achieving higher accuracy.

Warmup Steps
Warmup steps refer to the initial phase of training where the learning rate is gradually increased.

Residual Dropout
Residual dropout is a regularization technique applied to the output of each sub-layer in the Transformer model.

Label Smoothing
Label smoothing is a regularization technique that improves accuracy and BLEU score by making the model more unsure.

Newstest2014
Newstest2014 is a specific evaluation dataset used in the WMT 2014 competition.

Newstest2013
Newstest2013 is a development dataset used to evaluate the performance of models.<SEP>Newstest2013 is a development set used to measure the change in performance of the Transformer model on English-to-German translation.

GPUs
GPUs (Graphics Processing Units) are used to train the model by multiplying the training time and number of GPUs used by an estimate of the sustained single-precision floating-point capacity of each GPU.

Beam Search
Beam search is a search algorithm used in the evaluation of the Transformer model for English-to-German translation.

Attention Heads
Attention heads are components of the Transformer architecture that are varied to evaluate their impact on model performance.

K80

K40

M40

Nal Kalchbrenner

Stephan Gouws
Stephan Gouws is acknowledged for providing fruitful comments, corrections, and inspiration.

TensorFlow

Floating Point Operations
Mathematical operations used to train a model, influencing training time and resource allocation.

Single-Precision Floating-Point Capacity
A measure of a GPU's ability to perform floating-point operations, impacting the speed of model training.

Model Variations
Different configurations of the Transformer model tested to evaluate the importance of individual components.

Development Set

Checkpoint Averaging
A technique used to improve model performance, not used in this specific evaluation.

Table 3
A table presenting the results of varying the Transformer architecture.

Attention Key
A component of the attention mechanism in the Transformer model.

Attention Value Dimensions
A component of the attention mechanism in the Transformer model.

Single-Head Attention

Perplexity
A measure of how well a probability distribution predicts a sample.

Byte-Pair Encoding
A method of encoding text into word pieces.

Base Model
The standard Transformer model used as a baseline for comparison.

Rows (A)
Refers to the section of Table 3 that shows the variations in the number of attention heads and the attention key and value dimensions.

Rows (B)
Refers to the section of Table 3 that shows the variations in attention key size.

Rows (C)
Refers to the section of Table 3 that shows the variations in model size.

Rows (D)
Refers to the section of Table 3 that shows the variations in dropout rate.

Dropout
A regularization technique used to prevent overfitting.<SEP>Dropout is a regularization technique used to prevent overfitting in neural networks, as described in the paper by Srivastava et al.

Rows (E)
Refers to the section of Table 3 that shows the variations in positional encoding.

Sinusoidal Positional Encoding
A method of encoding the position of words in a sequence.

Learned Positional Embeddings
A method of encoding the position of words in a sequence.

Multi-Headed Self-Attention
An attention mechanism that uses multiple attention heads.

Translation Tasks
Tasks involving the translation of text from one language to another.

Ensembles

Local, Restricted Attention Mechanisms
Attention mechanisms that only attend to a local region of the input.

Images, Audio and Video
